    <div>
        <h2>Dr. Casey Kirkpatrick</h2>
        <p>
            Dr. Casey Kirkpatrick is an Adjunct Research Professor in the Department of Anthropology at the University of Western Ontario. 
            She has extensive experience working and conducting research in the museum, laboratory, and archaeological field settings in 
            Canada, Jordan, Egypt, England, and Wales. She is also a co-founder and former Executive Director of the Paleo-oncology Research 
            Organization (PRO), which is devoted to the study of cancers in ancient remains, and the Ancient Cancer Foundation, which is 
            directed toward public outreach and fundraising for PRO. As a former Dental Assistant, Casey maintains a special interest in dental 
            anthropology in addition to her passion for paleopathology. She is the 'Head of Osteology' on the BYU Egypt Excavation Project, 
            which is an especially appropriate title given that she is documenting and studying the Fag El-Gamous cranial collection. This work 
            will provide new information about the lives and deaths of those interred at Fag El-Gamous. Along with Dr. R. Paul Evans, Casey 
            also enjoys co-teaching the on-site osteological field school for Egyptian inspectors. Casey is a Postdoctoral Researcher at the 
            Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology in Leipzig, where she investigates the origins and evolution of treponemal 
            diseases through the study of ancient bacterial DNA from pre-Columbian human remains from Central and South America.
        </p>
